  "prompt": "Biochemistry: What are the most common types of protein damage caused by reactive nitrogen species?",
  "response": "Reactive nitrogen species (RNS) can induce various types of damage to proteins, potentially leading to alterations in function and structure. The most common types of protein damage caused by RNS include:\n\n1. **Nitration**: One of the primary forms of damage is the nitration of tyrosine residues, forming 3-nitrotyrosine. This can affect the protein's activity, structure, and interactions with other molecules.\n\n2. **Oxidation**: RNS like peroxynitrite can oxidize sulfur-containing amino acids (cysteine and methionine), leading to the formation of disulfides or sulfinic/sulfonic acid derivatives, which can affect protein folding and function.\n\n3. **S-nitrosylation**: This modification involves the covalent attachment of a nitric oxide group to the thiol side chain of cysteine residues, forming S-nitrosothiols. This can regulate protein function, signaling pathways, and may protect against oxidative damage, but excessive S-nitrosylation can disrupt normal protein function.\n\n4. **Deamination**: RNS can cause deamination of amino acids, particularly asparagine and glutamine, leading to changes in protein structure and function.\n\n5. **Carbonylation**: RNS can lead to the formation of protein carbonyls, which are indicators of oxidative damage and can impair protein function.\n\nThese modifications can disrupt protein function, alter cell signaling pathways, lead to aggregation or degradation of damaged proteins, and are associated with various diseases, including neurodegenerative disorders, cardiovascular diseases, and inflammatory conditions. Addressing RNS-induced protein damage is an important area of research in understanding and potentially mitigating these effects.",
